Getting and setting components
Accessor functions pull a piece out of a date-time: year(), month(), mday() (day of month), yday() (day of year), wday() (day of week), hour(). (Wickham et al. 2023) The same functions set components (year(d) &lt;- 2020), or use update() to change several at once. And rounding — floor_date(), round_date(), ceiling_date() — snaps a date to a unit, which is exactly what you need to count “flights per week” before plotting. (Wickham et al. 2023)
flights |&gt;
  mutate(dep = make_datetime(year, month, day, hour, minute)) |&gt;
  count(week = floor_date(dep, "week")) |&gt;     # bucket into weeks, then
  ggplot(aes(week, n)) + geom_line()           # plot the weekly series

Appendix · the full mathematics

Why the denominator cancels (the heart of MCMC). The Metropolis acceptance ratio for a proposed move \theta \to \theta' (with a symmetric proposal) is

r = \frac{p(\theta'\mid \text{data})}{p(\theta\mid \text{data})}
= \frac{\,p(\text{data}\mid\theta')\,p(\theta')\,/\,p(\text{data})\,}
       {\,p(\text{data}\mid\theta)\,p(\theta)\,/\,p(\text{data})\,}
= \frac{p(\text{data}\mid\theta')\,p(\theta')}{p(\text{data}\mid\theta)\,p(\theta)} .

The intractable p(\text{data}) appears identically in numerator and denominator and cancels — so the sampler needs only the unnormalised posterior (likelihood × prior). Accept if r \ge 1; otherwise accept with probability r (in practice compare \log r to \log u, u\sim\text{U}(0,1), for numerical stability — exactly the np.log(rng.random()) &lt; lp - lt test in the code).
Why the chain targets the posterior. Metropolis satisfies detailed balance with respect to the posterior \pi: \pi(\theta)\,T(\theta\to\theta') = \pi(\theta')\,T(\theta'\to\theta), which makes \pi the chain’s stationary distribution. An ergodic chain then converges to \pi regardless of start, so its long-run samples are posterior draws.
Monte Carlo error. For M (roughly independent) posterior draws, a posterior mean estimate has standard error \approx \sigma_{\text{post}}/\sqrt{M} — the same 1/\sqrt{M} law as everywhere else, so more samples buy more precision (slowly). Autocorrelation in the chain inflates this via the effective sample size M_{\text{eff}} &lt; M.
Equal-tailed vs HPD, formally. The equal-tailed interval is [\,q_{0.025},\,q_{0.975}\,] from the posterior quantile function. The 95% HPD is \{\theta : p(\theta\mid\text{data}) \ge c\} for the largest c with total mass 0.95 — the shortest such region, and the level-set that gives the pirate his disconnected digging zones when the posterior is multimodal.
